Well, I hung the other nesting box during the day. Here's what it looks like in its rightful place in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", I hear someone ask.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and wasn't able to modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the entire setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2,600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a photo of the panel.
The gray box suspended on the side of the birdhouse houses the battery.
The full charge gives me about 4 hours of energy.
I call that a feature. Like that birds can also have a bit of intimacy.
Initially, I didn't know if the internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points that I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and orient it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do it when I set up more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
Now, for reasons that are escaping me for the moment, the camera is offline. It turned off barely an hour after sunset.
The battery charge may have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Maybe it couldn't charge completely in a bit less than half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a telemetry system for the battery. I might add one in a future revision.
