Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C plate that I used to plug in the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP didn't connect right away, let's wait for a few minutes.
An hour later: still offline.
It looks like it's restarting in a loop and triggering the Tasmota reset functionality.
I think the board is just terrible. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look at what I found in the workshop.
An 24 V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden by a tree) that it goes down to almost nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I will wait until tomorrow to see if it's enough for this installation or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So, either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they have changed the specs.
Good news, everyone!
They have changed the specifications and the one I have is H.S.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12 V, 10 W panel.
That's why I don't erase my old emails.
Hear, look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of energy. It will only have taken a bit more than two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today. So I'm not sure if this solar panel (probably broken) is capable of generating enough energy to do anything.
Let's wait and see.
Last news: I've installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
Maybe everything will shut down at sunset, but let's wait and see.
By the way, I'm using Home Assistant's ping integration to monitor if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not too bad.
